# Lab 01 — Active Directory Setup

## Overview

In this lab I installed the Active Directory Domain Services role on Windows Server 2022 and promoted the server to a domain controller. This is the foundation of the entire lab environment. Every other lab in this series depends on having a working domain controller.

## Environment

| Component | Details |
|---|---|
| Server OS | Windows Server 2022 |
| Platform | VMware Workstation Pro |
| Domain Name | support.local |

## What is Active Directory

Active Directory Domain Services is a Microsoft directory service that allows administrators to manage users, computers, and resources across a network from one central location. When a server is promoted to a domain controller it becomes the authority for authentication and authorization within the domain. Any user or computer that joins the domain will check in with the domain controller to verify credentials and apply policies.

## Steps

### Step 1 — Open Server Manager
When Windows Server 2022 boots it opens Server Manager automatically. From the dashboard I clicked **Add roles and features** to launch the installation wizard.

### Step 2 — Select Installation Type
On the installation type screen I selected **Role-based or feature-based installation** and clicked Next.

### Step 3 — Select Destination Server
On the server selection screen my server was already listed in the pool and selected by default. I clicked Next.

### Step 4 — Select Server Role
On the server roles screen I checked the box next to **Active Directory Domain Services**. A popup appeared asking to add the required features for AD DS. I clicked **Add Features** and then clicked Next.

### Step 5 — Features and AD DS Overview
On the features screen I left everything as default and clicked Next. The following screen gave an overview of AD DS. I clicked Next again.

### Step 6 — Confirm and Install
On the confirmation screen I checked the box for **Restart the destination server automatically if required** and clicked **Install**. The installation ran and completed successfully.

### Step 7 — Promote to Domain Controller
After the installation finished a yellow flag notification appeared in the top right of Server Manager. I clicked it and selected **Promote this server to a domain controller** to launch the Active Directory Domain Services Configuration Wizard.

### Step 8 — Configure the Forest
On the deployment configuration screen I selected **Add a new forest** and entered the root domain name:

```
support.local
```

I clicked Next to continue.

### Step 9 — Domain Controller Options
On the domain controller options screen I left all settings at default and set a password for **Directory Services Restore Mode (DSRM)**. This password is used to recover Active Directory in the event of a failure. I clicked Next.

### Step 10 — DNS Options
A warning appeared about DNS delegation. This is expected in a new lab environment with no existing DNS infrastructure. I clicked Next.

### Step 11 — NetBIOS Name
The wizard automatically assigned the NetBIOS name **SUPPORT** based on the domain name I entered. I left it as default and clicked Next.

### Step 12 — Paths
The paths screen showed the default locations for the AD database, log files, and SYSVOL folder. I left everything as default and clicked Next.

### Step 13 — Review and Prerequisites Check
I reviewed the options on the summary screen and clicked Next. The wizard ran a prerequisites check. A few yellow warnings appeared which is normal for a new environment. The check completed with the message that all prerequisite checks passed. I clicked **Install**.

### Step 14 — Restart and Log Back In
The server automatically restarted after the promotion completed. When it came back up I logged in using the domain administrator account:

```
SUPPORT\Administrator
```

### Step 15 — Verify in Active Directory Users and Computers
I opened **Active Directory Users and Computers** from the Tools menu in Server Manager. The domain `support.local` appeared in the left panel. I expanded it and confirmed the following default containers were present:

| Container | Purpose |
|---|---|
| Builtin | Default security groups built into Windows Server |
| Computers | Machine accounts for domain joined computers |
| Domain Controllers | Lists all domain controllers in the domain |
| ForeignSecurityPrincipals | Accounts from external trusted domains |
| Users | Default user accounts and security groups |

## Result

The server is now a fully functioning domain controller for the `support.local` domain. Active Directory is installed and verified. This environment is ready for the next lab.

